	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032597658?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {The chapter opens with a thought-provoking question, Are we currently living in a time of Frontier AI or are we at risk of traversing an irreversible path toward Frankenstein AI ? The authors postulate that secondary and postsecondary education are key to navigating an efficacious future amidst the unanticipated AI implications in cybersecurity. Additionally, this chapter provides a historical curricular perspective from 1968 to recent education initiatives by the Association of Computing Machinery and its partners. It traces the first occurrences of artificial intelligence and security through its six decades of computing curricular guidelines for computer science, cybersecurity, and data science. In 2014 with broad community engagement, the National Centers for Academic Excellence in Cybersecurity released version 1 of “Cyber AI Programs.” This Stoneman report identifies knowledge and student learning outcomes for two emerging pathways, AI for Cybersecurity Programs and Security of AI Programs. ABET’s Computing Accreditation Commission is updating its general and program criteria for computer science, cybersecurity, data science, information systems, and information technology programs to incorporate appropriate AI education for its computing disciplines. Furthermore, this chapter analyzes federal and state policies that shape secondary computing education, focusing on how foundational computer science courses are intended to serve as on-ramps to AI and cybersecurity pathways. The analysis identifies several systemic challenges: inconsistent state-level adoption of computing standards, gaps in teacher certification and professional development, inequities in student access across geographic and socioeconomic contexts, and weak alignment between secondary programs and postsecondary or industry-recognized credentials. These factors collectively constrain the growth of a coherent national pipeline into AI and cybersecurity disciplines. Lastly, the chapter concludes with a call for future explorations in cybersecurity and AI education. © 2026 by The Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, Inc. All rights reserved.},
